        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer824267974" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17047022653456248481">What a beautiful and poignant read. This is McBride&apos;s tribute to his white mother. HIs story touches upon issues of racism, socioeconomics, identity and religion. From a young age, McBride struggled to find where he fit into this world as a black man with a white mother. At an early age, trying to find answers, he asked his mother what colour is God. Her response, &quot;He is the color of water.&quot; The story is juxtaposed along with his mother&apos;s, with the challenges they both faced defining themselves.</span>
  <span id="freeText17047022653456248481" style="display:none">What a beautiful and poignant read. This is McBride's tribute to his white mother. HIs story touches upon issues of racism, socioeconomics, identity and religion. From a young age, McBride struggled to find where he fit into this world as a black man with a white mother. At an early age, trying to find answers, he asked his mother what colour is God. Her response, "He is the color of water." The story is juxtaposed along with his mother's, with the challenges they both faced defining themselves. What she impressed upon all 12 children as being most important were education and getting 'religioned.' Despite the circumstances, she ensured this success in her children as she saw all 12 graduate from University. A great read. 4 stars. </span>
