  <span id="freeText17666721811604428099" style="display:none">I've had a copy of this for years and while I hadn't quite forgotten I had it, it had slowly slipped further and further down on my list of books to read. Recently I saw a copy of it in a shop, and it reminded me that I had a copy at home and I should finally read it. I had thought that I would read it one sitting, given it's short length, but it ended up taking me a few days, mainly because I kept rereading particularly brilliant lines, and because occasionally I had to take a little break from it, especially when his mother shared particularly challenging aspects of her youth, or her grief as an adult <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[she was widowed twice <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. Ruth McBride Jordan was a fascinating woman, and I can see why her son was so determined to write this book. <br /><br />James McBride's writing is brilliant, and I look forward to reading his novels. </span>
